The whereabouts of the original material is not known. The specimen illustrated by d’Archiac & de Verneuil (1842 : pl. 36 fig. 1) does not exist in the de Verneuil collection at the University of Lyon, where other original specimens of this work are located (Emmanuel Robert, written comm.,
April 8 th , 2021
). However, the description and illustration by d’Archiac & de Verneuil (1842) allows the species to be characterised ( Fig. 53 ). The only available specimen MB.C.7695 corresponds well with the one illustrated by d’Archiac & de Verneuil (1842) , in conch form as well as sculpture and suture line. It can therefore, with little doubt, be considered conspecific. It is herewith proposed as the neotype of the species.

Only a short portion of the suture line is visible in the ventral area. The external lobe is parallel-sided with a median saddle that reaches about half the height of the lobe. The E1 lobe is very narrow and very deep (
Fig.51A
).
